=> “To configure OAuth with Keycloak, we create a realm, client, users, and roles in Keycloak, then configure Spring Boot as an OAuth2 Resource Server using issuer-uri. 
The client authenticates with Keycloak and receives a JWT access token. That token is sent in the Authorization header to the REST API. 
Spring Security validates the JWT signature, issuer, and expiry using Keycloak public keys, then creates an authenticated security context for authorization.”

Realm = Group of users + apps. E.g. HR realms, Sales realm
Client = application (Web, mobile, API) that connects to Keycloak for login
Users = These are actiual users - Employees, Customers, Admins
Roles = Roles define permission. Assign role to users per client.
Identity Providers =  External login option. For instance, GitHub, Facebook
Protocols = langiages Keyclock uses to talk to apps securly. These are OIDC(OpenID Connect) and SAML

Authentication Protocls: When 2 different applications talk to each other they need to authenticate with each other.
OIDC(OpenID connect) - Modern and used in most apps
  - Built on top of OAuth2
  - Uses JWT tokens
  - Works with modern apps: React, Angular, Spring Boot, Node.js, mobile apps

SAML - To integrate with older enterprise apps

Need following properties to set in application:
1. spring.security.oath2.client.registration.oauth2-authorization-code-flow.client-id=oauth2-authorization-code-flow // provided by keyalock
2. spring.security.oath2.client.registration.oauth2-authorization-code-flow.client-secret=          // provided by keyalock
3. spring.security.oath2.client.registration.oauth2-authorization-code-flow.scope=openid,profile,roles,email //permission
4. spring.security.oath2.client.registration.oauth2-authorization-code-flow.autherization-grant-type=authorization_code
5. spring.security.oath2.client.registration.oauth2-authorization-code-flow.redirect-uri=http://localhost:8080/login/oauth2/code/
6. spring.security.oath2.client.provider.oauth2-authorization-code-flow.issuer-uri=Keylockuri

