-> On server side using need to use converter - Spring Security filter roles from token for client ID. Then create authority(SimpleGrantedAuthority) by prefixing with "Role_".
   - realm_access = global level role
   - resource_access = client level role access
   - Spring Security does not usually persist Keycloak roles server-side. It extracts roles from JWT claims, converts them into GrantedAuthority, and stores them temporarily
     inside the Authentication object in the SecurityContextHolder for the current request/session.Without storing them, Spring would need to repeatedly parse the token and 
     re-evaluate permissions everywhere. It can use .hasRole("ADMIN"), @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')"). 
     Spring needs a single authenticated user object accessible everywhere.

     But it does not store in DB because JWT is stateless. Since JWT authentication is stateless, the server reconstructs the authentication object from the token on every 
     request instead of permanently storing user roles in the database or session.

     Incoming Request -> JWT Token Validated -> Roles extracted from token -> Authentication object created -> Stored in SecurityContext -> Controllers/services use it for authorization

